The paper discusses a tool for converting rules into OWL axioms, which is relevant to artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and machine learning (cs.LG) as OWL is a popular language for representing knowledge in these fields. The tool also involves a user evaluation, which falls under the category of human-computer interaction (cs.HC) or software engineering (cs.SE). Additionally, the use of OWL axioms suggests a connection to databases (cs.DB) and natural language processing (cs.CL).
